liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The heads of the UN's major humanitarian agencies as well as international charities have called for an "immediate humanitarian ceasefire" in Gaza in a rare joint statement. Signatories from the World Health Organization, UNICEF, Save the Children and 15 others signed the letter calling the bombardment of Gaza by Israel "horrific". "An entire population is besieged and under attack, denied access to the essentials for survival, bombed in their homes, shelters, hospitals and places of worship. This is unacceptable," the letter said. Scores of aid workers have been killed including 88 UNRWA colleagues – the highest number of United Nations fatalities ever recorded in a single conflict— the letter added. "We renew our call for the immediate and unconditional release of all civilians held hostage."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: UN groups, humanitarian organisations call for ceasefire in rare joint statement

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israeli military activity in Gaza appears to have ramped up significantly over the past 24 hours, with fighter jets carrying out at least 450 strikes on the territory and Israeli troops confirmed to have surrounded Gaza City. Israeli media is reporting ground troops are likely to enter the city either today or tomorrow, marking a new stage in Israel's invasion of the Gaza Strip that is likely to lead to a significant increase in casualties on both sides of the conflict. The latest map from independent X account @War_Mapper, which tracks troop movements in conflict zones such as Gaza, Ukraine, Mali and Sudan, shows Israeli troops advancing south along the Mediterranean coastline, towards Israeli-controlled territory south of Gaza City. The ABC is unable to independently verify real-time conflict mapping, but the account is widely considered credible and its updates are based on publicly available information.
